When I was going to college at Penn State I picked up the game of rugby at the end of my junior year, absolutely fell in love with the sport, and have been playing ever since. After moving to Green Bay, I started playing with the Green Bay Rugby Club. I can't play in many matches (a Saturday work schedule doesn't match up well with their Saturday games), but I do practice and play in tournaments when I can to stay active with the club. GBRFC is coming off one of its most successful years in recent history and moving up a division to D-II from D-III. As part of that move, they're starting a brand-new D-4 developmental side to give new players a chance to learn the game the best way possible-- by actually playing in competitive matches.

But to do this, we need more numbers! If you're an athlete interested in something new or if you're just looking to try something different to stay active, come check out a practice. All you need is yourself, a mouth guard, and a pair of cleats. Playing time will be in NO short supply on the D-4 side this season, and doesn't require nearly the travel the D-2 side will.

Come on out!!!

Green Bay Packers Tight End Andrew Quarless told reporters Monday last Wednesday was: "Probably the saddest day of my life" -- according to ESPN.

The hardest and saddest day in one persons life is to bury their child. 
Saying hello and goodbye at the same time is something we are not designed to do as parents. Signing a birth certificate and a death certificate in same moment. Saying goodbye to your dreams, hopes, and life for that child, their daughter is the worst pain in the world.
So sorry for your loss, you are not alone. Prayers to the families involved in this tragedy. My heart breaks for you.
